This paper discusses network traffic obfuscation and its role in circumventing internet censorship. It covers technical aspects of networking and cryptography, making it likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of deep-packet inspection (DPI) and network traffic analysis, which falls under the cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) sub-category. The paper also touches on the challenges of censorship circumvention, which could fall under the cs.CY (Computers and Society) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the latest research on detecting obfuscation efforts, which could fall under the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) or cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-categories.
